<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="331" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,289,638]" pageId="1" pageNumber="331">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,289,314]" pageId="1" pageNumber="331">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body length larger than 10.0 mm. Shape of the body oval with a ratio of length versus width of the body larger than 1.39 (
<figureCitation box="[358,426,325,350]" captionStart="FIGURE 1. A" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1709,1731]" captionTargetBox="[180,1383,187,1676]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[170,1388,183,1684]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. A: Calagasma margarita Bergroth, 1914. French Guiana. Dorsal view drawn by Bergroth (1914). Scale = 2 mm. B: Epipedus histrio Spinola, 1837. Brazil. Lectotype ♀ conserved at MRSN, dorsal view drawn by Rolston (1987), montage of his 3 separate figures (dorsal view, pronotum and right corium). Stippled areas correspond to a rufous (red-brown) color. Scale = 2 mm. C: E. histrio Spinola, 1837. Brazil, Rio de Janeiro (Corcovado mountain) 1961, Alvarenga &amp; Seabra leg. ♀ specimen conserved at UFPR, dorsal view. Scale = 2 mm. Photo Jocelia Grazia, 2016. D: C. margarita Bergroth, 1914. French Guiana. syntype ♂ conserved at MZHF, dorsal view. Scale = 2 mm. Photo Pekka Malinen (MZHF), 2016. E: C. margarita Bergroth, 1914. French Guiana, Roura (Montagne des Chevaux RN 2 pK 22) 26. VII. 2014, SEAG leg. ♂ specimen, dorsal view. Scale = 2 mm. Collection Roland Lupoli. Photo Roland Lupoli, 2015. F: same in partial lateral view. G: Epipedus rolstoni Lupoli, sp. nov. holotype ♀ conserved at AMNH, dorsal view. Scale = 2 mm. Photo Jocelia Grazia, 2016. H: Calagasma eclipsa Lupoli, sp. nov. French Guiana, 1913 Dr Bongrand leg. holotype ♂ conserved at MNHN, dorsal view. Scale = 2 mm. Photo Roland Lupoli, 2016. I: same in ventral view. J: same in lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/260744/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="331">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
C &amp; 1G). Mandibular plates reflexed along lateral margins, converging over clypeus apically. Antennae 4-segmented: antennomers I surpassing apex of head, antennomers II with black spot at the tip, longer than antennomers III (not seen in 
<taxonomicName box="[612,730,397,421]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Epipedus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="331" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rolstoni">
<emphasis box="[612,730,397,421]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="331">E. rolstoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because they are missing). Anterolateral margins of pronotum convex. Corium with black deep contrasting punctations. Anterolateral border of exocorium flat. Apices of tibiae triangular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="331" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,289,638]" pageId="1" pageNumber="331">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,505,530]" pageId="1" pageNumber="331">Comments.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rolston" box="[347,521,505,530]" pageId="1" pageNumber="331" refString="Rolston, L. H. (1987) Diagnosis of Epipedus Spinola and redescription of the type species, E. histrio Spinola (Hemiptera: Pentatomidae). Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 95 (1), 69 - 72." type="journal article" year="1987">Rolston (1987)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned the mandibular plates strongly reflexed along lateral margins, the antennomers I surpassing apex of head, the anterolateral margins of pronotum strongly reflexed and tibiae with apex flattened or broadly rounded, as diagnosis characters of 
<emphasis box="[860,971,577,601]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="331">
<taxonomicName box="[860,967,577,601]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Epipedus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="331" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Epipedus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but not the other ones above. The other characters he mentioned are not diagnostic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
